To add to Aleksander&#39;s answer, inside the [`return-response` policy][1], there are two ways you can compose the final body

1. Using policy expressions

```csharp
&lt;set-body&gt;@{
    var output = new
    {
        success = true,
        var1 = context.Variables[&quot;var1&quot;]
    };
    return JsonConvert.SerializeObject(output);
}&lt;/set-body&gt;
```

2. Use liquid templates

```xml
&lt;set-variable name=&quot;var1body&quot; value=&quot;@((IResponse)context.Variables[&quot;var1&quot;]).Body.As&lt;string&gt;())&quot; /&gt;
&lt;set-body template=&quot;liquid&quot;&gt;{
&quot;success&quot;: true,
&quot;var1&quot;: &quot;{{context.Variables[&quot;var1body&quot;]}}&quot;
}&lt;/set-body&gt;
```

You can read more about the [`set-body` policy][2] in its doc.


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/api-management-advanced-policies#ReturnResponse
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/api-management/api-management-transformation-policies#SetBody

